  <!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
  <section class="tool-info-section" aria-label="How Base64 encoding works">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number" aria-hidden="true">[01]</span>
        <h2>How Base64 Encoding Works</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="section-desc">Base64 converts binary data into a <strong>safe ASCII string</strong> using 64 printable characters (A | Z, a | z, 0 | 9, +, /).</p>

      <div class="tool-info-grid">
        <div class="tool-info-card">
          <span class="tool-info-card-number" aria-hidden="true">1</span>
          <h3>Input Bytes</h3>
          <p>Your text is first converted to raw bytes using UTF-8 encoding. Each character becomes 1 | 4 bytes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-info-card">
          <span class="tool-info-card-number" aria-hidden="true">2</span>
          <h3>Split Into Groups</h3>
          <p>Bytes are grouped into sets of 3 (24 bits), then split into four 6-bit values. Padding (<code>=</code>) fills any remainder.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-info-card">
          <span class="tool-info-card-number" aria-hidden="true">3</span>
          <h3>Map to Characters</h3>
          <p>Each 6-bit value maps to one of 64 characters. The result is ~33% larger than the original but entirely ASCII-safe.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- VISUAL EXAMPLE -->
      <div class="b64-example">
        <div class="b64-example-header">
          <h3>Example</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="b64-example-body">
          <div class="b64-example-row">
            <span class="b64-example-label">Input:</span>
            <code class="b64-example-value">Hello</code>
          </div>
          <div class="b64-example-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><polyline points="19 12 12 19 5 12"/></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="b64-example-row">
            <span class="b64-example-label">ASCII bytes:</span>
            <code class="b64-example-value">72 101 108 108 111</code>
          </div>
          <div class="b64-example-arrow" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="12" y1="5" x2="12" y2="19"/><polyline points="19 12 12 19 5 12"/></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="b64-example-row">
            <span class="b64-example-label">Base64:</span>
            <code class="b64-example-value b64-example-value-accent">SGVsbG8=</code>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- USE CASES -->
  <section class="tool-usecases-section" aria-label="Base64 use cases">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number" aria-hidden="true">[02]</span>
        <h2>Common Use Cases</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="section-desc">Base64 is used across the web and in <strong>almost every modern stack.</strong></p>
      <div class="tool-usecases-grid">
        <div class="tool-usecase-card">
          <span class="tool-usecase-icon" aria-hidden="true">ðŸ–¼ï¸</span>
          <h3>Embedding Images in HTML/CSS</h3>
          <p>Convert small images to Data URIs (<code>data:image/png;base64,...</code>) to reduce HTTP requests and speed up rendering.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-usecase-card">
          <span class="tool-usecase-icon" aria-hidden="true">ðŸ“§</span>
          <h3>Email Attachments (MIME)</h3>
          <p>Email protocols (SMTP) use Base64 to encode binary attachments so they can travel through text-only channels.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-usecase-card">
          <span class="tool-usecase-icon" aria-hidden="true">ðŸ”‘</span>
          <h3>API Authentication</h3>
          <p>HTTP Basic Auth encodes <code>username:password</code> as Base64 in the <code>Authorization</code> header. Used in REST APIs worldwide.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-usecase-card">
          <span class="tool-usecase-icon" aria-hidden="true">ðŸª™</span>
          <h3>JWT Tokens</h3>
          <p>JSON Web Tokens use Base64url encoding for the header and payload segments. Every JWT you see is Base64 encoded.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-usecase-card">
          <span class="tool-usecase-icon" aria-hidden="true">ðŸ’¾</span>
          <h3>Data Storage in JSON/XML</h3>
          <p>When you need to embed binary data inside text formats like JSON or XML, Base64 is the standard approach.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-usecase-card">
          <span class="tool-usecase-icon" aria-hidden="true">ðŸ”</span>
          <h3>Cryptographic Operations</h3>
          <p>Hashes, keys, and certificates are often represented as Base64 strings for safe transport and storage.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="tool-faq-section" aria-label="Frequently asked questions">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-number" aria-hidden="true">[03]</span>
        <h2>FAQ</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="tool-faq-list">
        <div class="tool-faq-item">
          <button class="tool-faq-question" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Is Base64 encryption?</span>
            <svg class="tool-faq-chevron" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="tool-faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
            <p><strong>No.</strong> Base64 is an encoding scheme, not encryption. It doesn't provide security. Anyone can decode it. It's designed to safely represent binary data as ASCII text, not to hide information.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-faq-item">
          <button class="tool-faq-question" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Why is Base64 output larger than the input?</span>
            <svg class="tool-faq-chevron" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="tool-faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
            <p>Base64 represents every 3 bytes of input as 4 ASCII characters. This means the output is approximately <strong>33% larger</strong> than the original data. The trade-off is universal ASCII compatibility.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-faq-item">
          <button class="tool-faq-question" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>What is URL-safe Base64?</span>
            <svg class="tool-faq-chevron" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="tool-faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
            <p>Standard Base64 uses <code>+</code> and <code>/</code> which have special meaning in URLs. URL-safe Base64 replaces them with <code>-</code> and <code>_</code>, and often omits padding <code>=</code> characters. It's used in JWTs, OAuth tokens, and query parameters.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-faq-item">
          <button class="tool-faq-question" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Is my data safe? Does this tool send data to a server?</span>
            <svg class="tool-faq-chevron" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="tool-faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
            <p><strong>Your data never leaves your browser.</strong> All encoding and decoding is performed client-side using JavaScript's built-in <code>btoa()</code>, <code>atob()</code>, and <code>TextEncoder</code>/<code>TextDecoder</code> APIs. Nothing is sent to any server.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-faq-item">
          <button class="tool-faq-question" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Can I encode files and images?</span>
            <svg class="tool-faq-chevron" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="tool-faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
            <p>Yes. Switch to the "File Upload" tab to drag and drop any file up to 5 MB. The tool will output the Base64 string and optionally wrap it in a Data URI for direct embedding in HTML or CSS.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tool-faq-item">
          <button class="tool-faq-question" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>What character encoding does this tool use?</span>
            <svg class="tool-faq-chevron" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="tool-faq-answer" aria-hidden="true">
            <p>This tool uses <strong>UTF-8</strong> encoding by default. Unlike the browser's native <code>btoa()</code> which only supports Latin-1, this tool correctly handles all Unicode characters including emoji and CJK characters.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

